Yet other sermons contain passages in which he speaks with evident contempt of auriculas confession, calling it (as in the third volume) a human invention and a notorious fraud, taking its rise from Innocent III.1 There are, he says, two kinds of confession, one before God‚ the other before men, and the latter is an invention of rnen. Only confession to God is necessary to salvation. And in another sermon (pp. 55—57) he exposes the abuses connected with auriculas con· fession2 which ought on their account to be abolished. Here we have clearly a direct contradiction.

ln Sermon XXXIII Wyclif speaks (p. 289) of the merit of fasting (de bono ieiunio); in another sermon he makes light of fasting. The greed of the priests, he says (p. 55) orders fasting,3 Christ and the apostles did not set much store by it.4

Equally contradictory is his teaching about purgatory.

Whilst he says in the LVlh sermon that the greatest work of charity that can be shown to a dead man is to shorten his suffering in purgatory (p. 433); whilst in the same sermon he speaks of those who are burnt in Hell according to the sins which they have committed (p. 432), in the second sermon he makes light of prayers for the dead, and sets forth a doctrine which was accepted and perfected by the TaboriteS, who, as is well known, rejected purgatory.5
